    outlook: "The immediate future hinges on whether diplomatic channels can be reactivated and what new concessions or frameworks might emerge. Key catalysts to watch include any statements from the US State Department or the Iranian Foreign Ministry, potential mediation efforts by European powers or the United Nations, and the reactions of other major oil producers like Saudi Arabia and the UAE. Markets will be highly sensitive to any signs of renewed talks or further escalation. Further market volatility is almost guaranteed, and governments globally will likely explore strategies to mitigate the inflationary impact, including potential strategic petroleum reserve releases or domestic policy adjustments. The long-term outlook remains uncertain, with a delicate balance between geopolitical maneuvering and economic necessity.",
    conclusion: "The stalling of US-Iran peace talks serves as a stark reminder of the fragile balance between geopolitics and global economic stability. While earlier hopes pointed towards a new era of cooperation and stabilized energy markets, the current reality signals renewed uncertainty and upward pressure on global oil prices. From the petrol pump in the UK to investment decisions on the Nifty 500, the repercussions of this diplomatic impasse will be felt worldwide, underscoring the critical need for continued diplomatic engagement to foster a more predictable and prosperous global environment.",
